aws::graph::propositions: Cessna 207 Aircraft Information
Cessna 207 is a development of the Cessna U206C.
Cessna 207 was introduced for the 1969 model year.
Cessna 207 has a stretched cabin compared to the U206C.
Cessna 207's stretched cabin allows for a seventh seat.
Cessna 207 is powered by a 300 hp Continental IO-520-F engine.
Cessna 207 has a gross weight of 3,800 lb (1,724 kg).
Cessna 207 is also known as Skywagon 207.
The 1970 model year of Cessna 207 introduced a new control wheel design.
The 1970 model year of Cessna 207 introduced an optional gray instrument panel.
The 1970 model year of Cessna 207 introduced an optional mortuary variant.
The mortuary variant of Cessna 207 has room for a single casket.
The 1970 model year introduced a turbocharged variant called T207 Turbo Skywagon 207.
T207 Turbo Skywagon 207 is powered by a 300 hp Continental TSIO-520-G engine.
The 1973 model year of Cessna 207 introduced larger, padded control wheels.
The 1973 model year of Cessna 207 introduced revised avionics.
The 1973 model year of Cessna 207 introduced bonded-cabin doors.
The 1973 model year of Cessna 207 introduced a new glareshield.
The 1973 model year of Cessna 207 introduced new wheel fairings.
The 1974 model year of Cessna 207 introduced integral cabin door armrests and handles.
The 1974 model year of Cessna 207 introduced revised avionics.
The 1974 model year of Cessna 207 introduced an optional 28V electrical system.
Continental IO-520-F is an engine with 224 kW power output.
Continental TSIO-520-G is a turbocharged engine with 224 kW power output.

text:
### Cessna 207
207 Skywagon 207
Introduced for the 1969 model year as a development of the U206C with a stretched cabin allowing for a seventh seat, powered by a 300 hp (224 kW) Continental IO-520-F engine, and with a gross weight of 3,800 lb (1,724 kg).  The 1970 model year introduced a new control wheel design, an optional gray instrument panel, an optional mortuary variant with room for a single casket, and a turbocharged variant powered by a 300 hp (224 kW) Continental TSIO-520-G engine as the T207 Turbo Skywagon 207.  1973 introduced larger, padded control wheels, revised avionics, bonded-cabin doors, a new glareshield, and new wheel fairings.  1974 introduced integral cabin door armrests and handles, revised avionics, and an optional 28V electrical system.
